ce:section.ce:para:
Due to the significance of regulation of pH in biological and chemical systems, precisely detecting pH variation is of great concern all the time. Interestingly, the developed N,S-CQDs were found to exhibit a sensitive response to change in pH value. As a result, they can serve as powerful fluorescent probes for pH determination. To explore the analytical performance of N,S-CQDs, the relationship between the fluorescence intensity of the probes and various pH values from 0.93 to 12.48 under 360 nm excitation was plotted. Based on the results shown in Fig. 3
                        a–c, it can be observed that the fluorescence intensities of N,S-CQDs at 550 nm gradually decrease under highly acidic conditions, while they tend to remain stable when the pH value exceeds 7.00. According to the pH sensing, the pK
                        a value of the probes can be calculated to be 4.10 (detailed calculations could be found in Section 4, SI). Moreover, there is an excellent linearity between the fluorescence intensity and pH over the ranges from pH 0.93 to 7.00, in view of the linear regression equation y = 131.6x - 139.1, with a linear coefficient (correlation coefficient squares, R

                           2
                        ) of 0.9956. Compared with previous reports [37–41] (Table 1
                        ), N,S-CQDs in our work possessed larger stokes shift, exhibited higher sensitivity, and could detect lower pH. Furthermore, benefiting from their large ensemble Stokes Shift, N,S-CQDs can effectively avoid self-quenching in long-time cellular imaging. Therefore, the as-synthesized N,S-CQDs can be powerful biosensing platforms to differentiate tumor cells from healthy cells due to different pH of intracellular environment.
